  "Managing Effects –&nbsp;Part 2": "",
  "media loading": "",
  "In the previous lesson, we established three rules for managing effects in React. They were...": "",
  "Rule #0": "",
  "When a component renders, it should do so without running into any side effects": "",
  "Rule #1": "",
  "If a side effect is triggered by an event, put that side effect in an event handler": "",
  "Rule #2": "",
  "If a side effect is synchronizing your component with some outside system, put that side effect inside useEffect": "",
  "Now that you have some rules to guide you, let's stress test them a bit with some more advanced use cases.": "",
  "Up until this point, all of our examples have been side effects that are local to the user's device –&nbsp;getting their battery level, accessing local storage, changing the document's title. But when you think of side effects, especially as someone building for the web, the one that most likely comes to mind first is network requests.": "",
  "Without the ability to manage the complexity of asynchronous side effects like network requests, React would be mostly useless. Thankfully, we've already established a nice mental model for how we can do this.": "",
  "Sandbox - CodeSandbox": "",
  "Now before we jump into the code, I want you, knowing what you know now about how to handle side effects in React, to think through how you might implement this.": "",
  "Your first intuition is probably to put it in an event handler. Whenever the user interacts with our carousel, we'll make a network request to asynchronously fetch the next Pokémon. That seems perfectly reasonable – unfortunately, it's the wrong approach.": "",
  "\"whenever the user interacts with our carousel\"": "",
  "Before we worry the async bits, let's build out the basic logic for our carousel first. Again, the entire premise of this app is to synchronize our component with the result of calling the Pokémon API. To do that, we'll need some state. Specifically, we'll add an \u0000SKIP#142\u0000 state to keep track of the \u0000SKIP#143\u0000 of the Pokémon we're currently viewing and a \u0000SKIP#144\u0000 state to keep track of the actual Pokémon data. Our \u0000SKIP#145\u0000 state will default to \u0000SKIP#146\u0000 since that's the \u0000SKIP#147\u0000 of the first Pokémon, Bulbasaur.": "",
  "We'll then encapsulate the async logic for fetching a Pokémon into a function called \u0000SKIP#151\u0000. Now, whenever we invoke \u0000SKIP#152\u0000 passing it an \u0000SKIP#153\u0000 of the Pokémon we want to fetch, we'll get back an object with an \u0000SKIP#154\u0000 if there was one or a \u0000SKIP#155\u0000 of the Pokémon data if there wasn't.": "",
  "Now the fun part. We want to synchronize our local \u0000SKIP#159\u0000 state with the PokéAPI according to our local \u0000SKIP#160\u0000 state. That's a fancy way of saying whenever our local \u0000SKIP#161\u0000 state changes, we want to invoke \u0000SKIP#162\u0000 passing it the new \u0000SKIP#163\u0000. We'll do that by calling \u0000SKIP#164\u0000 inside of \u0000SKIP#165\u0000 and then updating our \u0000SKIP#166\u0000 state with the result.": "",
  "There are a few interesting things to point out with the code above.": "",
  "isn't": "",
  "Second, you may be wondering why we declared a new \u0000SKIP#174\u0000 function inside of our event. This is purely aesthetic and was done so that we could use \u0000SKIP#175\u0000/\u0000SKIP#176\u0000 inside of \u0000SKIP#177\u0000.": "",
  "Third, this is \"tutorial\" code. We're pretending like loading and error states don't exist. Unfortunately, you can't write tutorial code at work, so let's fix that.": "",
  "First, we'll need to add two new pieces of state to our component, \u0000SKIP#178\u0000 and \u0000SKIP#179\u0000. Because \u0000SKIP#180\u0000 is invoked as a result of rendering, including the initial render, we'll initialize \u0000SKIP#181\u0000 to \u0000SKIP#182\u0000 (and \u0000SKIP#183\u0000 to \u0000SKIP#184\u0000).": "",
  "Now we need our effect to manage our new \u0000SKIP#186\u0000 and \u0000SKIP#187\u0000 states. Thankfully our \u0000SKIP#188\u0000 function makes this easy since it's so explicit if there's an error.": "",
  "What we'll do is whenever our effects runs, reset \u0000SKIP#189\u0000 and \u0000SKIP#190\u0000 back to their default values before we make the network request. Then, once we get back a response, if there's an error, we'll update \u0000SKIP#191\u0000, and if not, we'll update \u0000SKIP#192\u0000 before setting \u0000SKIP#193\u0000 to \u0000SKIP#194\u0000.": "",
  "State Batching": "",
  "Don't get freaked out over the multiple, separate invocations of our updater functions (\u0000SKIP#199\u0000, \u0000SKIP#200\u0000, \u0000SKIP#201\u0000). Remember, React \"batches\" those together intelligently so there's no wasted renders.": "",
  "You could argue at this point the hardest parts are behind us. It appears we've successfully abstracted the arduous async side effect bits into \u0000SKIP#202\u0000, and are now synchronizing our component with the PokéAPI.": "",
  "At this point, all we need to do is update the UI to both show our active Pokémon and allow the user (or the app itself) to change it via our Carousel. These components are extraneous to the point of this post, so I'll just paste them in and you can view them if you'd like.": "",
  "Notice the simplicity of our app now. Because we've told \u0000SKIP#207\u0000 to synchronize our local \u0000SKIP#208\u0000 state with the PokéAPI according to \u0000SKIP#209\u0000, we've taken what has historically been the most complex part of building a web app, an asynchronous side effect, and made it an implementation detail behind simply updating \u0000SKIP#210\u0000 via our \u0000SKIP#211\u0000 and \u0000SKIP#212\u0000 functions.": "",
  "here's a hint.": "",
  "Whenever we call \u0000SKIP#214\u0000, because it's an asynchronous request, we have no idea how long that request will take to resolve. It's completely possible that, while we're in the process of waiting for a response, our Carousel updates \u0000SKIP#215\u0000, which causes a re-render, which causes our effect to run again&nbsp;with a different \u0000SKIP#216\u0000.": "",
  "whatever request was resolved last": "",
  "You can see this by scrolling back up and playing around with the app. Change the active Pokémon on the carousel as fast as you can.": "",
  "That's a pretty subpar experience. How would you go about fixing it?": "",
  "Thankfully, React makes this pretty easy with the last remaining feature of \u0000SKIP#221\u0000 you haven't seen yet: the \"cleanup\" function.": "",
  "If you return a function from your effect, React will call that function each time before it ever calls your effect again, and then one final time when the component is removed from the DOM.": "",
  "We can see this in action by adding a cleanup function to our effect that logs the \u0000SKIP#225\u0000 that the effect is associated with.": "",
  "Now play around with the app and notice the logs. Specifically, think of how we can leverage this knowledge of our cleanup function in order to ignore stale effects.": "",
  "Power of JavaScript™": "",
  "Whenever the effect runs, let's make a variable called \u0000SKIP#234\u0000 and set it to \u0000SKIP#235\u0000. Then, whenever the cleanup function runs (which we know will only happen when the effect is stale), we'll set \u0000SKIP#236\u0000 to \u0000SKIP#237\u0000.": "",
  "Then, all we have to do before we call \u0000SKIP#238\u0000 or \u0000SKIP#239\u0000, is check to see if \u0000SKIP#240\u0000 is \u0000SKIP#241\u0000. If it is, then we'll do nothing.": "",
  "Now, regardless of how many times \u0000SKIP#246\u0000 changes, we'll ignore every response that isn't in the most recent effect. This not only makes our app more performant, but it also improves the UX since React will now only re-render with the latest Pokémon.": "",
  "Now I know you're having the time of your life, but this'll be the last scenario we look at for now –&nbsp;and it's one you'll see often.": "",
  "Let's say we were writing software for a company that administers certifications for employees. To earn a certification, an employee must pass an online test by a certain percentage. Part of the test is that for every time the employee tabs away from the current window, they lose a percentage.": "",
  "How would we go about encapsulating this requirement into a React component, letting the student know how many times they've tabbed away?": "",
  "Here's a hint": "",
  "You can use the document's \u0000SKIP#247\u0000 event to detect when the page is no longer visible.": "",
  "First, let's add some state to track the number of times the employee has tabbed away. We'll call this \u0000SKIP#248\u0000 and we'll also add some UI for the user to see their count.": "",
  "Now the tricky part. We need to listen for the \u0000SKIP#252\u0000 event and update our \u0000SKIP#253\u0000 state accordingly. Since we're synchronizing the document's visibility status with our component, we'll use \u0000SKIP#254\u0000.": "",
  "First let's add our event listener. Remember, whenever you add an event listener, you also need to remove it when the component is removed from the DOM or you'll have a memory leak. \u0000SKIP#255\u0000's cleanup function makes this simple.": "",
  "Now all we need to do is update our \u0000SKIP#260\u0000 function to increment our \u0000SKIP#261\u0000 state whenever the document is no longer visible. Your first intuition might be to do something like this –&nbsp;where we add \u0000SKIP#262\u0000 to our dependency array and then increment it by \u0000SKIP#263\u0000 inside of \u0000SKIP#264\u0000.": "",
  "Whenever the document's \u0000SKIP#269\u0000 is no longer visible, we increment \u0000SKIP#270\u0000 by one. Simple, right? Yes, but actually no. In fact, even though our app appears to be working fine, there's a major problem. Can you spot it?": "",
  "Via our dependency array, we've told React that our effect depends on our \u0000SKIP#271\u0000 state (which is true). That means, whenever \u0000SKIP#272\u0000 changes, React will re-render and then, once it's done, re-invoke our effect.": "",
  "The problem is every time React calls our effect, we're removing the previous event listener and adding a new one. That's... not ideal. We can see this in action if we add some logs to our effect and tab away and back to this page.": "",
  "We're in a weird spot. We only want React to add our event listener once, on the initial mount, but we need to include \u0000SKIP#277\u0000 in the dependency array because we're using it inside of the effect to calculate the new \u0000SKIP#278\u0000 state.": "",
  "What's interesting about this example compared to our other examples is, even though we're using \u0000SKIP#279\u0000 in the effect, we're not using it as a way to synchronize our component with some external system – so we don't actually need React re-run the effect when it changes.": "",
  "Right now, and in almost every other scenario when you're updating state, you pass the state's updater function the value with which you want to replace the current state.": "",
  "However, an often overlooked aspect of this API is you're also able to pass the state's updater function a function itself, and when React invokes that function, it'll pass it the current state. You can then use that state to calculate the new state.": "",
  "In both of these examples, we're telling React to increment \u0000SKIP#284\u0000 by \u0000SKIP#285\u0000. However, the difference is in how we're getting access to the current state of \u0000SKIP#286\u0000 before we increment it. In the first example, we're relying on a closure –&nbsp;and therefore we have to specify \u0000SKIP#287\u0000 inside of the dependency array. In the second, we're not, since React will pass us the current state of \u0000SKIP#288\u0000 as an argument and therefore, we don't need to include it in the dependency array.": "",
  "With this knowledge, we can now update our example to remove \u0000SKIP#289\u0000 from the dependency array which prevents React from re-running our effect every time it changes.": "",
  "Hopefully at this point you're starting to get a solid grasp of how you can use the rules we've established to better establish a mental model for managing side effects in React.": "",
  "Now before you go, there are a few smaller details I want to point out that didn't fit into the normal narrative flow of these last few lessons, but I think are important to know.": "",
  "Why is this helpful? You can think of \u0000SKIP#299\u0000 as a stress test of our 3 rules. If render is not pure or you're incorrectly managing side effects, \u0000SKIP#300\u0000 will (aggressively) uncover that.": "",
  "It's controversial, but the whole goal of \u0000SKIP#301\u0000 is to make it more obvious that you're doing something wrong –&nbsp;which I think is a reasonable goal. If you stick to the rules we've established, \u0000SKIP#302\u0000 will be mostly irrelevant for you.": "",
